    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-12-09T15:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-12-09T15:25:00-05:00" n="345"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                <head>345. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d345fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967–69,
                        POL 1 <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>-US. Secret; Exdis. Repeated to
                        Amman, Tel Aviv, and Cairo.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-12-09T20:25:00+00:00">December 9, 1968,
                        2025Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8369. Subject: <gloss target="#t_UARG1">UARG</gloss> reaction to <gloss
                        target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> reaction.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> PermRep <persName corresp="#p_KMAE1">El
                            Kony</persName> called on <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJR1">Wiggins</persName> Dec 9 to convey message from
                            <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> Riad. El-Erian, <persName
                            corresp="#p_RM2">Mohammed Riad</persName> and <gloss target="#t_Amb1"
                            >Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWB1">Buffum</persName> present.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Translating from statement drafted in third person, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KMAE1">El Kony</persName> read four points: <list>
                            <label>A.</label>
                            <item>FonMin surprised at <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> reaction
                                of disappointment to his memo<note n="2" xml:id="d345fn2">See <ref
                                        target="#d337fn2">footnote 2, Document 337</ref>.</note>
                                replying to seven points Secretary raised with him.</item>
                            <label>B.</label>
                            <item>FonMin regrets he cannot agree with US that <gloss
                                    target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> memo will not help <persName
                                    corresp="#p_JG1">Jarring</persName> because latter has informed
                                Egyptians to contrary.</item>
                            <label>C.</label>
                            <item>
                                <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> reaction will not be helpful to
                                    US-<gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> dialogue.</item>
                            <label>D.</label>
                            <item>It has been hoped this dialogue would promote understanding but
                                now it seems it might create misunderstanding.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KMAE1">El Kony</persName> added his own hope that
                        after further study of memo US would have different reaction from our
                        initial one. <persName corresp="#p_WJR1">Wiggins</persName> said if memo
                        helps <persName corresp="#p_JG1">Jarring</persName>, that is good. Certainly
                        early sections of memo (which <persName corresp="#p_KMAE1">El
                            Kony</persName> called historical expose) look backward rather than
                        forward. Perhaps we were expecting too much in a tragic situation which
                        moves so painfully slow. If memo does prove to be helpful element, we will
                        gladly admit our reaction to it was wrong.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWB1">Buffum</persName> inquired whether <gloss
                            target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> memo envisages no settlement without Syria
                        being part of it. <persName corresp="#p_RM2">Mohammed Riad</persName>
                        declared principle of withdrawal underlies everything. While issues of Canal
                        and Tiran Strait can be separated out as <gloss target="#t_UAR1"
                        >UAR</gloss>-Israel bilateral problems, principle of withdrawal is common
                        problem for <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>, Jordan and Syria. <persName
                            corresp="#p_WJR1">Wiggins</persName> pointed out that this brings
                        situation back to basic impasse. <persName corresp="#p_BWB1"
                            >Buffum</persName> suggested Riad’s explanation seems something like
                        adding apples and pears because Syria has not accepted <gloss
                            target="#t_Res1">Res</gloss> 242. <persName corresp="#p_KMAE1">El
                            Kony</persName> expressed view that if principle of withdrawal is
                        recognized fully, other issues would fall in place.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJR1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Wiggins</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
